I"á<p>The subchapter 3.5 of <a href="http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/book/BDA3.pdf"><strong>Bayesian Data Analysis Third Edition</strong></a> gives distributional results of Bayesian inference for the parameters of a multivariate normal distribution. Additionally, this article discusses the derivation of those results in gory details.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/images/bayes-theorem.jpg"><img src="/assets/images/bayes-theorem.jpg" alt="img1" class="img-responsive" /></a><em><center>$\pmb{\text{Figure 1}}$: Example of a normal distribution consisting a horde of rabbits. Image taken from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem">Wikipedia</a>, some rights reserved.</center></em></p>

<p>The <em>posterior</em> density of the normal model consists of a <em>likelihood</em> distribution, $\Pr(y \mid \theta)$, and a <em>prior</em> distribution, $\Pr(\theta)$. Specifically,</p>

\[\begin{align}
	y_i \mid \theta &amp;\sim \text{N}(\theta, \sigma^2) &amp;&amp; \text{A normal distribution with mean = }\theta \text{ and variance = }\sigma^2\text{, for }i=1, \ldots, n \\
	\theta          &amp;\sim \text{N}(\mu_0, \tau_0^2)  &amp;&amp;  \text{A normal distribution with mean = }\mu_0 \text{ and variance = }\tau_0^2.
\end{align}\]
